abstract: I have heard some comment among Democrats in this city on the letter signed "F.G.R.," which appeared in THE NEW YORK TIMES on Nov. 14, urging the formation in this city of an anti-Bryan, anti-Tammany Democratic association. I cordially indorse the suggestion. Col. Bryan will doubtless be nominated again for the Presidency and again defeated. Tammany having, through its leader, Richard Croker, supported this unwise nomination, will have to bear responsibility for the result.

abstract: The house of Herman Buek, a retired merchant, living at 1,019 Lafayette Avenue, Brooklyn, was robbed late on Wednesday night. abstract: CHICAGO, Nov. 30. -- The University of Chicago finished her triumphant series to-day by defeating Brown by a score of 17 to 0. Only twice in the game did Brown menace the Maroon goal, and each time Chicago braced with fine spirit and saved her goal from the rushes of the Rhode Islanders. From centre to end the Maroons outpointed Brown, and gave an exhibition of consistent defense which she has seldom surpassed.

abstract: ELIZABETH, N.J., Dec. 1. -- Justus Morris died to-day at his home in Linden. He was born in Lower Rahway in 1821. He first worked on a farm, then made money as a painter, and later was a successful real estate speculator here. He owned some of the best business property in the city. He served on the Board of Chosen Freeholders, and was defeated for Mayor on an independent ticket.

abstract: WASHINGTON, Dec. 2. -- The Republican members of the Senate probably will hold a caucus next Tuesday afternoon to make provision for the reorganization of the committees. These will be filled, and in cases in which the Republicans are in the minority on committees steps will be taken so to change the membership as to give them control.

abstract: RED BANK, N.J., Dec. 2. -- Lucien O. Appleby is preparing to go into thoroughbred horse breeding on an even more extensive scale than ever at his farm here. abstract: The crown of Russia is at present presumably the richest in diamonds. Besides several valuable collections in the imperial Treasury, there are three crowns entirely composed of these stones. That of Ivan Alexiowitch contains 881, that of Peter the Great 847, and that of Catharine II. 2,526. One of its most remarkable diamonds is the "Orloff," now set in the top of the imperial sceptre, and on this account is sometimes called the "Sceptre" diamond.

abstract: BERLIN, Dec. 3. -- The advance of the Bank of England's rate dominates the attention of the Berlin money market. At first it was supposed that this would not have an immediate effect here, the British balances having been much reduced of late, but since London exchange has already shown a rising tendency the market reckons with the possibility that the Reichsbank will soon raise its rate to 7 per cent.

abstract: AUSTIN, Texas, Dec. 3. -- Information reaching here to-day from Ortiz. abstract: Anxiety is felt by officials in charge of Brooklyn's water supply because of the unusually low level of water in the main storAge reservoir of the system at Rockville Centre, L. I. abstract: ASHTABULA, Ohio, Dec. 4. -- A most remarkable snowstorm struck Northeastern Ohio to-day, the first of the season. At 5 o'clock A.M. the air was filled with large flakes, and by noon, by actual measurement, there was a nineteen-inch depth on a level. This evening it is a little less than three feet deep on a level, and in places four feet.

abstract: READING, Penn., Dec. 7. -- Fire in the extensive hosiery mill of the Nolde  Hoist Company to-day destroyed the plant, and caused the death of one person, besides injuring fifty-seven other employes of the company. Of the fifty-seven persons who were injured, thirty -- all women and girls -- are seriously hurt.

abstract: The qualifying preliminary rounds in the Class B amateur billiard tournament at the Knickerbocker Athletic Club were finished yesterday. In the afternoon Threshie defeated Tobias, and in the evening Hendrick disposed of Miller. This leaves the two Boston men, Cutler and Threshie, Hevner of Philadelphia, Kellogg of Chicago, and Smith of St. Louis to play in the finals, which will be started to-morrow. None of the New York players succeeded in qualifying.

abstract: BINGHAMTON, N.Y., Dec. 20. -- John Gardiner, aged sixty, residing on the western outskirts of this city, to-night shot his wife, aged twenty-nine, in the right breast and left arm. He then retired to his house. Where he awaited the coming of the officers at a window. On catching sight of the brass buttons of the policemen he raised the revolver to his head and sent a bullet crashing through his brain, death being instantaneous.

abstract: BANGOR, Me., Dec. 22. -- At this date Winter has not arrived in Maine, and the ground is as bare as in August, while the rivers are entirely free from ice. abstract: The phrase "Dutch courage" has been popularly used to reflect upon the bravery of the Hollander. Strange that this should be as we view him in the light of history! abstract: Fish was in great demand at Rome, and incredible sums might be made by fish ponds or wasted on them. abstract: The coloring power which can be derived from coal tar is quite astonishing. From one ton of good cannel coal are obtained by distillation about twelve gallons of coal tar. abstract: From the veranda some clematis hangs down in beautiful festoons, and in early Autumn it is a mass of bloom. But, alas for the scent of it! abstract: BACOLOT, Island of Nefiros, Nov. 7. -- The mountains of Negros run down its centre and length, and between the foothills of this range and the sea there is a belt of lowlands averaging in width from five to twenty miles. abstract: BERLIN, Dec. 24. -- The advance in the Reichsbank rate to 7 per cent. had a great effect upon the security of the market. Values declined only moderately. abstract: The Suydam Homestead at Bushwick and Johnson Avenues, Brooklyn, which is over 200 years old, and the oldest of the few Dutch houses now left in the Williamsburg section, will be razed to the ground in a few days. abstract: PHILADELPHIA, Penn., Dec. 27. -- This evening the first large ball of the season took place at Horticultural Hall, Philadelphia, given by the Benedicts. abstract: A recent number of Caffaro of Genoa contains a curiously literal rendering in Italian of Rudyard Kipling's Poem, "The Absent-Minded Beggar." It is entitled "Il Mendicante Distratto." It will be seen that even in the title the spirit of the words has been lost, for although "distratto" is good enough for "absent-minded." "mendicante" signifies "beggar" in the most literal sense -- a mere taker of aims.

abstract: SEATTLE, Washington, Dec. 29. -- In an attempt to rob a Ballard street car late last night a highwayman was shot and killed. There were eight passengers aboard when two men wearing masks boarded the car, one at the front and the other at the rear. abstract: LONDON, Dec. 30. -- The reported sortie from Ladysmith, resulting in the capture of a Boer position, is not confirmed, and apparently is only a Kafir story. A Chieveley dispatch, dated Dec. 29, makes no mention of it. The same message shows renewed activity upon the part of the British, apparently preparatory to some action.

abstract: The arrival of the new year will be celebrated in many ways throughout the city to-day and to-morrow. Many of the Roman Catholic churches will take advantage tonight of the Papal permission for the celebration of midnight mass. At St. Patrick's Cathedral a pontifical mass will be celebrated by Archbishop Corrigan, and Father Lavelle, rector of the cathedral, will preach the sermon.
